</p><p>It follows that, for <span class="texhtml"><i>w</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> = <i>z</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>/<i>m</i></span>, <span class="texhtml"><i>w</i><sub>1</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>w</i><sub>2</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>w</i><sub>3</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>w</i><sub>4</sub><sup>2</sup> = <i>rp</i></span>, and this is in contradiction with the minimality of&#160;<i>m</i>.
</p><p>In the descent above, we must rule out both the case <span class="texhtml"><i>y</i><sub>1</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>2</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>3</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>4</sub> = <i>m</i>/2</span> (which would give <span class="texhtml"><i>r</i> = <i>m</i></span> and no descent), and also the case <span class="texhtml"><i>y</i><sub>1</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>2</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>3</sub> = <i>y</i><sub>4</sub> = 0</span> (which would give <span class="texhtml"><i>r</i> = 0</span> rather than strictly positive).  For both of those cases, one can check that <span class="texhtml"><i>mp</i> = <i>x</i><sub>1</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>x</i><sub>2</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>x</i><sub>3</sub><sup>2</sup> + <i>x</i><sub>4</sub><sup>2</sup></span> would be a multiple of <i>m</i><sup>2</sup>, contradicting the fact that <i>p</i> is a prime greater than <i>m</i>.
